      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20
Last Monday Elon Musk announced that he had bought about 9% of Twitter Inc.=
=E2=80=99s stock.  I wrote:Look this all makes complete sense, obvious, int=
uitive, simple sense. If you are the richest person in the world, and annoy=
ing, and you constantly play a computer game, and you get a lot of enjoymen=
t and a sense of identity from that game and are maybe a little addicted, t=
hen at some point you might have some suggestions for improvements in the g=
ame. So you might leave comments and email the company that makes the game =
saying =E2=80=9Chey you should try my ideas.=E2=80=9D And the company might=
 ignore you (or respond politely but not move fast enough for your liking).=
 It might occur to you: =E2=80=9CLook, I am the richest person in the world=
; how much could this game company possibly cost? I should just buy it and =
change the game however I want.=E2=80=9D Even if your complaints are quite =
minor, why shouldn=E2=80=99t you get to play exactly the game you want? Eve=
n if you have no complaints, why not own the game you love, just to make su=
re it continues to be exactly what you want? The game is Twitter, the riche=
st person in the world is Elon Musk, and: [so on].One thing about this mode=
l is that it is fundamentally=C2=A0selfish. If you want the game to have a =
certain feature, and you buy the company and tell it to add the feature, an=
d the game designers come to you and say things like =E2=80=9Cmost other pl=
ayers do not want this feature=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cour analysis shows that=
 if we add this feature a lot of players will quit=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwe =
will lose a lot of our advertising revenue if we add this feature,=E2=80=9D=
 you will not care. Those are not considerations that are relevant to you, =
as a very rich person who bought a game company to make the game more fun.=
=C2=A0You are not doing this to make everyone else happy, or to maximize th=
e value of the business. You are doing this to maximize your own enjoyment =
of the game. You have a lot of money and are looking to spend=C2=A0it, on m=
aking the game better=C2=A0for you.So I imagined Musk, as Twitter=E2=80=99s=
 new largest shareholder, going to Chief Executive Officer Parag Agrawal an=
d asking him to tweak Twitter to make the font bigger on Musk=E2=80=99s twe=
ets. I imagined Agrawal objecting:Agrawal:=C2=A0I just feel like we want to=
 make a good product for all of our millions of users? I feel like that is =
going to improve profitability in the long run and, as our largest sharehol=
der, you in particular stand to benefit from=E2=80=94Musk:=C2=A0Oh I don=E2=
=80=99t care even a little bit about that, if your stock doubles that is ro=
unding error on my net worth, I just love tweeting and want to meddle a bit=
 to optimize it for my personal needs.Well that was a week ago and since th=
en a lot has changed, and then changed back. On Tuesday,  Agrawal announced=
 that Musk would be joining Twitter=E2=80=99s board of directors. And then =
last night he announced that he wouldn=E2=80=99t:Elon Musk has decided not =
to join our board. Here=E2=80=99s what I can share about what happened.The =
Board and I had many discussions about Elon joining the board, and with Elo=
n directly. We were excited to collaborate and clear about the risks. We al=
so believed that having Elon as a fiduciary of the company where he, like a=
ll board members, has to act in the best interests of the company and all o=
ur shareholders, was the best path forward. The board offered him a seat. =
=E2=80=A6Elon=E2=80=99s appointment to the board was to become officially e=
ffective 4/9, but Elon shared that same morning that he will no longer be j=
oining the board.Here is Musk=E2=80=99s amended Schedule 13D filing. You ca=
n sort of put the pieces together:Musk: I want the font bigger on my tweets=
.Agrawal: Why don=E2=80=99t you join our board of directors?Musk: Yes! Then=
 I can=C2=A0definitely tell you to make the font bigger on my tweets, and y=
ou=E2=80=99ll have to listen.Musk=E2=80=99s poor lawyer: Actually if you ar=
e a director you will have a fiduciary duty to act in the best interests of=
 the company and all of its shareholders.Musk: Wait a minute.=E2=80=9CElon =
is our biggest shareholder and we will remain open to his input,=E2=80=9D s=
ays Agrawal. Now, if Musk wants to change how Twitter operates, he can get =
a meeting with Agrawal whenever he wants, and ask for whatever he wants. If=
 Agrawal says no, he can threaten to buy more stock and take over the compa=
ny. (His agreement to join the board=C2=A0came with a standstill, preventin=
g him from going above 14.9% of the stock =E2=80=9Cfor so long as Mr. Musk =
is serving on the Board and for 90 days thereafter,=E2=80=9D but I guess if=
 he never joins the board he never has to abide by that?[1]) Or he can twee=
t mean things about Agrawal, which might be just as effective. If Musk asks=
 for ridiculous things that Agrawal thinks are not in the best interests of=
 Twitter,=C2=A0then Agrawal has his own fiduciary duty to say no, though he=
 might find it hard to say no to his largest shareholder and noisiest user.=
 But=C2=A0Musk=C2=A0will have no duties to anyone; he can do his best to ma=
ke Twitter as fun as possible for himself, whatever anyone else thinks.Over=
 the weekend he did quite a lot of that. Yesterday morning,=C2=A0after he d=
eclined the board seat but before that was announced, Musk  tweeted a poll =
proposing to =E2=80=9CConvert Twitter SF HQ to homeless shelter since no on=
e shows up anyway.=E2=80=9D Later that day, he tweeted another poll, =E2=80=
=9Cthis time asking his followers whether they wanted to =E2=80=98delete th=
e w in twitter.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D (Both tweets were later deleted.) I am su=
re he enjoyed doing these dumb things! They were fun for him! If he was on =
the board, would he have proposed these things seriously? If not, would it =
be=C2=A0consistent with his fiduciary duties to propose them publicly? I du=
nno man, and I do not envy his lawyers, but at least they dodged this bulle=
t. Now he can tweet whatever jokes he wants about Twitter.Really it is hard=
 to imagine how he could have joined the board. In addition to the general =
idea of fiduciary obligations to shareholders,=C2=A0Twitter is a normal-ish=
=C2=A0public company and it has policies. Here is a collection of those pol=
icies. =E2=80=9COur board of directors has adopted our Corporate Governance=
 Guidelines,=E2=80=9D says Twitter in its securities filings.=C2=A0Here are=
 those=C2=A0Corporate Governance Guidelines, adopted by the board =E2=80=9C=
to assist the Board in the exercise of its responsibilities and to serve th=
e interests of the Company and its stockholders in a manner that is consist=
ent with its fiduciary duties.=E2=80=9D For instance:The Board believes tha=
t management speaks for the Company. Each director should refer all inquiri=
es from the press, members or others regarding the Company=E2=80=99s operat=
ions to management. Individual Board members may, from time to time at the =
request of the management, meet or otherwise communicate with various const=
ituencies that are involved with the Company. If comments from the Board ar=
e appropriate, they should, in most circumstances, come from the Chairman o=
f the Board or the Lead Independent Director in compliance with the Company=
=E2=80=99s External Communications Policy.Imagine Elon Musk going to his on=
boarding meeting for the Twitter board of directors[2]:Twitter=E2=80=99s la=
wyer: I=E2=80=99m going to go over the policies that apply to all of our di=
rectors, and that you have to agree to follow.Musk: [ignores lawyer, looks =
at phone, tweets about deleting the =E2=80=9Cw=E2=80=9D in =E2=80=9CTwitter=
.=E2=80=9D]Twitter=E2=80=99s lawyer: You can=E2=80=99t comment publicly abo=
ut Twitter. If anyone asks you for a comment, you should refer them to mana=
gement. If you want to speak publicly about Twitter you generally should ge=
t approval from management first.Musk=E2=80=99s poor lawyer:=C2=A0Ahahahaha=
hahahahahahahahaha  good luck with that one buddy.If you put Elon Musk on y=
our board of directors, either he has to stop being Elon Musk or you have t=
o stop being a normal public company. He is not going to stop being Elon Mu=
sk! =E2=80=9CWhat does seem clear,=E2=80=9D writes Ben Thompson,=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Cis that Musk realized that being a board member would suck, and, as n=
oted, Twitter now has to be even more open to his input.=E2=80=9DI want to =
make two points here. One is that traditionally activist investors=C2=A0wan=
t=C2=A0board seats. They want board seats not only because they want to cha=
nge how the company operates, but also because=C2=A0they believe that their=
 ideas are in the interests of all shareholders. When an activist says to a=
 company =E2=80=9Cyou should spin off your non-core businesses=E2=80=9D or =
=E2=80=9Cyou should do more share buybacks=E2=80=9D or whatever, they make =
an explicit case that this would make the stock price go up and be good for=
 all shareholders. Sometimes they=E2=80=99re wrong, and often management ar=
gues=C2=A0that they=E2=80=99re wrong, and that they=E2=80=99re looking out =
for their own short-term interests rather than the long-term interests of a=
ll shareholders. But the activists=E2=80=99 self-conception is that they ar=
e advocating on behalf of ordinary shareholders, and that they are actually=
 better representatives of all=C2=A0shareholders than management is.[3]With=
 Elon Musk this is all unnecessary. He=E2=80=99s not trying to win votes fr=
om other shareholders and is not interested in being a fiduciary for Twitte=
r. He just has a lot of money and wants to have some fun.=C2=A0The other po=
int is that, here in 2022, it is possible that=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cjust do a bunc=
h of random weird stuff to entertain=C2=A0Elon Musk=E2=80=9D=C2=A0is=C2=A0a=
 good strategy and=C2=A0will=C2=A0make the stock go up. I have spent too mu=
ch time around here writing=C2=A0a dumb playbook for corporate finance and =
investor activism in the 2020s. What you do is, you buy some stock in a com=
pany, and then you  mount an  activist campaign that is like =E2=80=9Cif I =
am put in charge of this company I will do more memes.=E2=80=9D The importa=
nt things in modern corporate finance are=C2=A0unhinged tweeting, public as=
sociation with Elon Musk=C2=A0and vague plans to accept Dogecoin for goods =
and services. Promising to do that stuff will make the stock go up. Will it=
 improve the economic fortunes of the company? I dunno;  it might. (Some co=
mpanies need cash, and being able to raise lots of cash by selling stock at=
 high prices is good.) But that isn=E2=80=99t really the point. The point i=
s that if you can make the stock go up then the stock will go up. The stock=
 price, not the economic fortunes of the company, is  the thing to maximize=
 here. And in modern markets you maximize the stock price with memes.If thi=
s is true then the person who is best suited to=C2=A0do=C2=A0it =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0even better than  Adam Aron, or  Ryan Cohen =E2=80=94=C2=A0is Elon Mu=
sk. He has more money than anyone else so he can easily buy an activist sta=
ke, he is good at unhinged tweeting already, and he has a unique ability to=
=C2=A0create=C2=A0a public association between a company and Elon Musk, whi=
ch by the  Elon Markets Hypothesis is the=C2=A0most important thing for a c=
ompany=E2=80=99s stock price.In one of Musk=E2=80=99s tweets this weekend, =
he suggested letting people pay for Twitter Blue (Twitter=E2=80=99s paid su=
bscription tier) with Dogecoin. That is how corporate finance works now: Th=
e thing you do is tweet some idle musings about accepting payment in Dogeco=
in, or even better =E2=80=94=C2=A0as here =E2=80=94=C2=A0get=C2=A0Elon Musk=
=C2=A0to tweet some idle musings about accepting payment in Dogecoin. Do yo=
u have to accept payment in Dogecoin? No, of course not, that has nothing t=
o do with anything, the point is that there are some meme buttons =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the Dogecoin button, the Elon Musk button, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and if=
 you press them the stock goes up.=C2=A0In many ways Tesla Inc. is the orig=
inal meme stock but it does make cars. Having a high stock price seems to b=
e good for Tesla=E2=80=99s ability to make cars, and having a high-profile =
chief executive officer seems to be good for Tesla=E2=80=99s ability to sel=
l those cars, but the main job really is to make cars.=C2=A0SpaceX, Musk=E2=
=80=99s other main company, makes space rockets. The space rockets seem to =
be fairly successful at traveling into space, and SpaceX is a private compa=
ny so=C2=A0meme-ing up its stock price is not a relevant consideration. I d=
on=E2=80=99t pretend to understand the Boring Company.My point is that in h=
is main three jobs Elon Musk is in charge of=C2=A0real companies=C2=A0that =
do=C2=A0stuff in the real world. He can, and does, add a lot of value =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0also he sometimes  subtracts a lot of value =E2=80=94 by being =
noisy on Twitter. But he can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0only=C2=A0do that. That is not =
the=C2=A0main=C2=A0source of value at those companies, or the=C2=A0main=C2=
=A0job of a CEO. You gotta make the cars, or the rockets or the tunnels.Twi=
tter, however, is Twitter.=C2=A0Its main product is tweets! Elon Musk can a=
dd a ton of value just by tweeting, without joining the board or weighing i=
n on questions of policy and strategy. And he can stay off the board and we=
igh in on policy and strategy as chaotically as he wants, because=C2=A0the =
questions of policy and strategy are=C2=A0about tweets. What=C2=A0an irresi=
stible opportunity for him.Anyway Twitter=E2=80=99s stock was down=C2=A0pre=
-open on this news, but as of noon today it was actually a bit higher than =
it was on Friday, and up about 18% from where it was before Musk announced =
his stake. Elon Musk will be doing weird stuff with Twitter for a while whe=
ther or not he=E2=80=99s on the board, and that has to be good for sharehol=
der value.Elsewhere here is a claim that Elon Musk is Satoshi Nakamoto?
