      Russia
   =20
 =20
If you are an American or European investment firm, and you bought dollar-d=
enominated Russian government bonds, do you have a preference between these=
 scenarios?=09Russia decides not to pay you back in dollars, and doesn=E2=
=80=99t. You complain, and sue, but Russia is a big country with nuclear we=
apons so your complaining doesn=E2=80=99t accomplish much.=09Russia really =
wants to pay you back, and has the money, but it chooses to launch a brutal=
 unprovoked invasion of another country, which causes the U.S. and much of =
the rest of the world to impose harsh sanctions including blocking dollar p=
ayments on its bonds, with the result that Russia can=E2=80=99t pay you bac=
k your dollars. Russia complains, and sues, but the U.S. is also a big coun=
try with nuclear weapons (and control over the dollar payments system) so i=
ts complaining doesn=E2=80=99t accomplish much.You might, right? Like in Sc=
enario 2, if Russia really does want to pay you, it might find a way around=
 the sanctions; a Russian finance ministry official might meet you in a par=
k with a bag of gold and say =E2=80=9Cnow we=E2=80=99re even.=E2=80=9D That=
=E2=80=99s better than getting nothing in Scenario 1. Also Scenario 2 might=
 seem a bit more temporary; maybe the war will end and you=E2=80=99ll get p=
aid in full.=C2=A0Still I suspect that the practical differences between th=
ese scenarios are not that big. In particular, once either of these scenari=
os occurs and you don=E2=80=99t get paid, will you want to lend more money =
to Russia in the future? =E2=80=9CThey might decide not to pay me back=E2=
=80=9D is a credit risk, and =E2=80=9Cthey might launch a war of aggression=
 and be unable to pay me back=E2=80=9D is a credit risk, and they are not s=
o different in their effects. =E2=80=9CNo this is not the bad Scenario 1, b=
ut the good Scenario 2,=E2=80=9D Russia can say, but I don=E2=80=99t think =
Scenario 2 is=C2=A0really that good?But people are very invested in  the me=
taphysics of this:Russia will halt bond sales for the rest of the year and =
take legal action if sanctions force it into a default on its debt, accordi=
ng to the country=E2=80=99s finance minister.Anton Siluanov=E2=80=99s comme=
nts in Russian newspaper Izvestia come days after the government breached t=
he terms on two bonds by paying investors rubles instead of dollars, and it=
s credit grade at S&P Global Ratings was cut to =E2=80=98selective default.=
=E2=80=99The threat of default has been hanging over Russia for weeks after=
 it was hit with sanctions because of its invasion of Ukraine. The governme=
nt in Moscow says it has the funds to meet its debt obligations and has rep=
eatedly blamed the restrictions for its difficulties in making bond payment=
s. Siluanov has said the U.S. and others are trying to force Russia into de=
fault.=C2=A0=E2=80=9COf course, we will sue, because we have taken all the =
necessary steps to ensure that investors receive their payments,=E2=80=9D h=
e said, according to Izvestia. =E2=80=9CIt will not be an easy process. We =
will have to very actively prove our case, despite all the difficulties.=E2=
=80=9DWho will they sue? Where? For what?=C2=A0Russia wants to vindicate th=
e metaphysical status of its default as not-really-a-default, but there is =
not really a good court for vindicating metaphysical status.Meanwhile, one =
problem with doing a fire-sale divestiture of your Russian operations is th=
at you are selling those operations at fire-sale prices  to Russian operato=
rs:Societe Generale SA agreed to sell its Rosbank PJSC unit to the investme=
nt firm of Russia=E2=80=99s richest man, taking a hit of about 3 billion eu=
ros ($3.3 billion) to exit the heavily sanctioned nation.The Paris-based ba=
nk signed an accord to sell its entire stake in Rosbank and its Russian ins=
urance subsidiaries to Vladimir Potanin=E2=80=99s Interros Capital, accordi=
ng to a statement on Monday. =E2=80=A6Potanin, 61, is the world=E2=80=99s 4=
3rd richest person with a net worth of $29.6 billion, according to the Bloo=
mberg Billionaires Index. He is president of MMC Norilsk Nickel PJSC, which=
 accounts for about 40% of global palladium output and 10% of refined nicke=
l, and has a stake in Russian company Petrovax Pharm.Potanin had avoided sa=
nctions by Western governments until Canada recently added him to its list.=
=C2=A0We have  talked about this dilemma before. One reason to divest from =
Russia is something like =E2=80=9CRussia is uninvestable and these assets a=
re worthless, so selling them at any price is great.=E2=80=9D In which case=
, sure. The other reason is something like =E2=80=9Cinvesting in Russia rai=
ses moral and public-relations problems, so we are getting out even though =
the assets are financially valuable.=E2=80=9D In which case, the people who=
 don=E2=80=99t care about the moral and public-relations problems are getti=
ng a sweet deal.
