      How=E2=80=99s Jared Kushner=E2=80=99s business going?
   =20
 =20
If you spend four years working in a high-level but informal White House jo=
b running Middle East policy, and in that job you=C2=A0advocate for policie=
s that favor Saudi Arabia, and then you leave that job and cash in by start=
ing an investment company to be funded largely by the Saudi sovereign wealt=
h fund, is it important for the investment company to be=C2=A0good? At inve=
sting? No, of course not; they are not giving you the money because you are=
 a good investor. It is always possible that someone at the Saudi sovereign=
 wealth fund will misunderstand, however. The New York Times reports:Six mo=
nths after leaving the White House, Jared Kushner secured a $2 billion inve=
stment from a fund led by the Saudi crown prince, a close ally during the T=
rump administration, despite objections from the fund=E2=80=99s advisers ab=
out the merits of the deal.A panel that screens investments for the main Sa=
udi sovereign wealth fund cited concerns about the proposed deal with Mr. K=
ushner=E2=80=99s newly formed private equity firm, Affinity Partners, previ=
ously undisclosed documents show.Those objections included: =E2=80=9Cthe in=
experience of the Affinity Fund management=E2=80=9D; the possibility that t=
he kingdom would be responsible for =E2=80=9Cthe bulk of the investment and=
 risk=E2=80=9D; due diligence on the fledgling firm=E2=80=99s operations th=
at found them =E2=80=9Cunsatisfactory in all aspects=E2=80=9D; a proposed a=
sset management fee that =E2=80=9Cseems excessive=E2=80=9D; and =E2=80=9Cpu=
blic relations risks=E2=80=9D from Mr. Kushner=E2=80=99s prior role as a se=
nior adviser to his father-in-law, former President Donald J. Trump, accord=
ing to minutes of the panel=E2=80=99s meeting last June 30.But those sorts =
of misunderstandings get straightened=C2=A0out between principals:But days =
later the full board of the $620 billion Public Investment Fund =E2=80=94 l=
ed by Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman, Saudi Arabia=E2=80=99s de facto rul=
er and a beneficiary of Mr. Kushner=E2=80=99s support when he worked as a W=
hite House adviser =E2=80=94 overruled the panel. =E2=80=A6Mr. Kushner plan=
ned to raise up to $7 billion in all, according to a document prepared last=
 summer for the Saudi fund=E2=80=99s board. But so far he appears to have s=
igned up few other major investors.In its most recent public filings with t=
he Securities and Exchange Commission, dated March 31, Mr. Kushner=E2=80=99=
s firm reported that its main fund had $2.5 billion under management, almos=
t entirely from investors based overseas. Most of that appears to be the $2=
 billion from Saudi Arabia.We  talk sometimes around here about people who =
pay money to government officials to influence policy and who then get in t=
rouble for using clumsy euphemisms. This is the opposite. This is how you d=
o it right!
