      Blockchain
   =20
 =20
At Wired last week, Andy Greenberg had a gripping and upsetting story about=
 how law enforcement brought down a child pornography website that accepted=
 payment in cryptocurrency, which made its proprietor and users fairly=C2=
=A0easy to trace. One interesting note=C2=A0is that the investigation start=
ed because some Internal Revenue Service agents were bored and=C2=A0started=
 looking around the blockchain for crimes:At loose ends in Bangkok, Gambary=
an and Janczewski spent much of their time idly contemplating what their ne=
xt case should be, browsing through Chainalysis=E2=80=99 blockchain-tracing=
 software Reactor to brainstorm ideas. Dark-web markets like AlphaBay seeme=
d to have been reduced to a shambles by the Thailand operation, and they=E2=
=80=99d take months or even years to recover. The agents considered taking =
on a dark-web gambling site. But illegal online casinos hardly seemed worth=
 their attention. ...Stuck in the terminal with hours to kill, they sat hal=
f-awake and bored, literally staring at the wall. To pass the hours, Gambar=
yan decided to try calling Chainalysis=E2=80=99 Levin to discuss next cases=
. When Levin picked up the phone, he had news to share. He=E2=80=99d been l=
ooking into a website that didn=E2=80=99t fit among the IRS=E2=80=99s usual=
 targets but that he hoped they=E2=80=99d be willing to check out: Welcome =
to Video.It=E2=80=99s not just that, if you do crimes using Bitcoin, the pu=
blic immutable blockchain makes it easier for authorities to find you. It=
=E2=80=99s that so many people do so many crimes using Bitcoin, and so many=
 of them are not good at covering their tracks,=C2=A0that browsing the publ=
ic immutable blockchain is a good way for the authorities to discover crime=
s they hadn=E2=80=99t even thought of before.=C2=A0
