bscribe at this link. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great B=
loomberg newsletters here. Thanks![1] Last week I  praised the brevity of t=
hat standstill agreement, but I suppose spending an extra paragraph on the =
somewhat odd case of =E2=80=9Cwhat happens to the standstill if he never jo=
ins the board in the first place?=E2=80=9D would have been a good investmen=
t.=C2=A0[2] In these imagined dialogues it is funny and instructive to imag=
ine Musk=E2=80=99s lawyer traveling with him to these meetings, but in fact=
 I sometimes doubt that Musk ever takes a lawyer anywhere.[3] This is true =
even in the modern world of environmental, social and governance investing.=
  ESG activists=C2=A0do=C2=A0argue that doing ESG stuff will be  good for t=
he long-term value of the company, make the stock go up, etc. But they also=
 recognize that other shareholders have non-financial interests, and they a=
rgue that they are representing those interests better than management is. =
Again they seek board seats, again because they view themselves as being=C2=
=A0better=C2=A0qualified than management to represent the interests of all =
shareholders. Even=C2=A0Carl Icahn=E2=80=99s=C2=A0activism for better treat=
ment of pigs at McDonald=E2=80=99s Corp. and Kroger Corp.=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=
=A0which sort of looks like=C2=A0a semi-retired rich guy pursuing an idiosy=
ncratic personal quest motivated by his daughter, and which he has defended=
  in emotional terms =E2=80=94=C2=A0at least involves a general principle. =
Musk=E2=80=99s activism involves deleting the =E2=80=9Cw=E2=80=9D from =E2=
=80=9CTwitter=E2=80=9D to give him some juvenile amusement.
