uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look this all makes complete sense, obvio=
us, intuitive, simple sense. If you are the richest person in the world, an=
d annoying, and you constantly play a computer game, and you get a lot of e=
njoyment and a sense of identity from that game and are maybe a little addi=
cted, then at some point you might have some suggestions for improvements i=
n the game. So you might leave comments and email the company that makes th=
e game saying =E2=80=9Chey you should try my ideas.=E2=80=9D And the compan=
y might ignore you (or respond politely but not move fast enough for your l=
iking). It might occur to you: =E2=80=9CLook, I am the richest person in th=
e world; how much could this game company possibly cost? I should just buy =
it and change the game however I want.=E2=80=9D Even if your complaints are=
 quite minor, why shouldn=E2=80=99t you get to play exactly the game you wa=
nt? Even if you have no complaints, why not own the game you love, just to =
make sure it continues to be exactly what you want? The game is Twitter, th=
e richest person in the world is Elon Musk, and: [so on].</p></blockquote><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing about this model is that it is fundam=
entally=C2=A0<em>selfish</em>. If you want the game to have a certain featu=
re, and you buy the company and tell it to add the feature, and the game de=
signers come to you and say things like =E2=80=9Cmost other players do not =
want this feature=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cour analysis shows that if we add th=
is feature a lot of players will quit=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwe will lose a l=
ot of our advertising revenue if we add this feature,=E2=80=9D you will not=
 care. Those are not considerations that are relevant to you, as a very ric=
h person who bought a game company to make the game more fun.=C2=A0You are =
not doing this to make everyone else happy, or to maximize the value of the=
 business. You are doing this to maximize your own enjoyment of the game. Y=
ou have a lot of money and are looking to <em>spend=C2=A0</em>it, on making=
 the game better=C2=A0<em>for you</em>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So =
I imagined Musk, as Twitter=E2=80=99s new largest shareholder, going to Chi=
ef Executive Officer Parag Agrawal and asking him to tweak Twitter to make =
the font bigger on Musk=E2=80=99s tweets. I imagined Agrawal objecting:</p>=
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Agrawal:</strong>=C2=A0I j=
ust feel like we want to make a good product for all of our millions of use=
rs? I feel like that is going to improve profitability in the long run and,=
 as our largest shareholder, you in particular stand to benefit from=E2=80=
=94</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Musk:</strong>=C2=A0Oh I don=E2=
=80=99t care even a little bit about that, if your stock doubles that is ro=
unding error on my net worth, I just love tweeting and want to meddle a bit=
 to optimize it for my personal needs.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Well that was a week ago and since then a lot has changed, and the=
n changed back. On Tuesday, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
