5px;">Russia</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are an American or European inv=
estment firm, and you bought dollar-denominated Russian government bonds, d=
o you have a preference between these scenarios?</p><ol style=3D"list-style=
-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">Russia decides not to pay you back in dollars, and doesn=E2=
=80=99t. You complain, and sue, but Russia is a big country with nuclear we=
apons so your complaining doesn=E2=80=99t accomplish much.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Russia really wants to pay you back, and has the m=
oney, but it chooses to launch a brutal unprovoked invasion of another coun=
try, which causes the U.S. and much of the rest of the world to impose hars=
h sanctions including blocking dollar payments on its bonds, with the resul=
t that Russia can=E2=80=99t pay you back your dollars. Russia complains, an=
d sues, but the U.S. is also a big country with nuclear weapons (and contro=
l over the dollar payments system) so its complaining doesn=E2=80=99t accom=
plish much.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You might, right? Like in=
 Scenario 2, if Russia really does want to pay you, it might find a way aro=
und the sanctions; a Russian finance ministry official might meet you in a =
park with a bag of gold and say =E2=80=9Cnow we=E2=80=99re even.=E2=80=9D T=
hat=E2=80=99s better than getting nothing in Scenario 1. Also Scenario 2 mi=
ght seem a bit more temporary; maybe the war will end and you=E2=80=99ll ge=
t paid in full.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still I suspect that =
the practical differences between these scenarios are not that big. In part=
icular, once either of these scenarios occurs and you don=E2=80=99t get pai=
d, will you want to lend more money to Russia in the future? =E2=80=9CThey =
might decide not to pay me back=E2=80=9D is a credit risk, and =E2=80=9Cthe=
y might launch a war of aggression and be unable to pay me back=E2=80=9D is=
 a credit risk, and they are not so different in their effects. =E2=80=9CNo=
 this is not the bad Scenario 1, but the good Scenario 2,=E2=80=9D Russia c=
an say, but I don=E2=80=99t think Scenario 2 is=C2=A0really that good?</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But people are very invested in <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27330343.276596/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMTAvcnVzc2lhLXRvLWhhbHQtYm9u=
